title: For Sale/Trade:  Group Industries Uzi
postcontent: Looking to sell or trade my Group industries Uzi carbine. Not 100% perfect, but in great shape overall. This gun was manufactured in the 80's by Group Industries, a company that no longer exists. However Vector Arms (a quality, current production Uzi manufacturer) now builds their Uzi's using Group Industires' recievers. It's somewhat of an uncommon firearm in this part of the world but a very simple, reliable design. Israel has used Uzi's since the 1950'sThese semi auto Group Industries are pretty rare, and I am told that few were made in this green color. I am not sure of the exact round count but it's relatively low. This gun has the full size barrel and is chambered in 9mm. They also make barrels and bolts that allow you to shoot .45 acp or .22lr out of this gun.Comes with a sling and four magazine repair kits-(2) 25rd and (2) 32rd. I could throw in a little ammo for the right trade.I value this gun in the neighborhood of $1,200 but I could use the cash so I'll sell it for $1000. Research what these go for and you'll see that my price is more than reasonable. title: For Sale:  Antique Colt 45 Nedbuntline special
postcontent: One of the things Hollywood does well is create legends. And one of the most enduring to come out of the television Westerns of the 1950s and ’60s was the Buntline Special, a Colt Single Action Army with a 12" barrel.  This elongated hogleg made its theatrical appearance in “The Life And Legend Of Wyatt Earp,” which aired on ABC from 1955 to 1961 and starred Hugh O’Brian, who carried it in a Bohlin-made double rig with a holster featuring an extended drop (necessary for the foot-long barrel to clear leather in a timely manner).  But the Colt Buntline wasn’t conjured up by a screenwriter. It was based in fact-sort of. Back in Earp’s day, Colt customers could order extra-long barrels at a dollar an inch for anything over 7½". Approximately 31 such guns-with barrels ranging from 10" to 16"-were produced from 1876 through 1884. However, in Stuart N. Lake’s book, Wyatt Earp: Frontier Marshall, upon which the TV series was based, he relates that five of these stretch-tubed SAAs were presented by dime novelist Edward Zane Carroll Judson, who used the pen name Ned Buntline, to Earp and four other Dodge City lawmen-Bat Masterson, Bill Tilghman, Charlie Bassett and Neal Brown-in 1876. Historically, it is doubtful this ever happened, but the story was too good to be ignored.  Just as the TV cowboy craze corralled Colt into reissuing the Single Action Army in 1955, in 1957 “Earpmania” caused the company to bring out a Buntline Special, which remained in the line until 1975, with 4,060 produced. Most were blued and case-hardened with rubber stocks but some had two-piece walnut grip panels and 65 were nickeled.  The guns were serial numbered in the same SA suffix range as standard second generation Peacemakers, but their 12" barrels were stamped “Colt Buntline Special .45.” Buntlines produced through the late 1960s also had a three- or four-digit BB (Buntline Barrel) assembly number on the underside of their barrels. During the 1980s and ’90s many Buntlines were rebarreled, adding to their scarcity. Thus, like all Second Generation Colts, the Buntline has climbed in collectability.  This  Buntline is in 100 percent condition, with a barely discernable drag line on the cylinder and comes with a wooden case that slides out and 6 antique 45 bullets and a Ned bunt line plate.Call or text REDACTED

title: For Sale:  DDI AK 47 - Magpul furniture, brand new in box!
postcontent: I've just been hit with one of those fun unexpected bills and need to cash in one of my rifles to cover it since that's about all I ever invest in.  I just picked up this DDI not even 2 months ago and with our busy lives, kids, work, etc I haven't even taken it out to shoot yet.  So, it's brand new and just been sitting in my safe.  Of course I have everything that came in the box and the original box still, with the addition of a tapco mag I'll throw in for you since Atlantic Firearms (who purchsed through) doesn't send you the stock standard cap mag.One thing I'll say about the rifle is it's put together better than absolutely anything you'll find under a $1000, and stands up next to my arsenals in fit and finish without a doubt.  If you don't know DDI a quick internet search will provide you with nothing but glowing reviews and this is the company that specializes in their proprietary fenocite finish, which is more of a process done to certain/a majority of the parts of the rifle leaving the surface tougher than chrome or nitrite finish and brings the surface hardness up to something like 60 rockwell.  The action is super smooth and unlike many AK's with just a slight cant, when you look down this rifle the first thing you notice is just how dead on straight everything is.  DDI really takes their time to build a top-end rifle and incorporates the same kind of care that companies like Arsenal do without the outrageous price tag.  Although I'll never complain about my Arsenal, it was worth the price, this DDI in my opinion is simply priced much lower for the same quality, if not more considering the treatment they do to the parts.  Fenocited barrels are supposed to last a whole third longer than chrome or nitrite.Anyhow, can't say enough about this DDI and wish I didn't have to sell it as they are REALLY hard to find and go out of stock almost instantly when distributors like Atlantic actually get them in, which might happen once or twice a year.  DDI is a small company that produces super high quality small batch Ak's, and I'm sure are upsetting companies like Arsenal as they're quickly becoming known for producing rifles with equal fit and finish and at a lower price point.  I'll take a couple good pics with my wife's ipad as soon as she gets home or when I remember to, for now I just threw the pic from the DDI sight on this posting so you can see the model, this one I have for sale is the one in the pic and in the exact same brand new condition.Any questions feel free to call, thanks!  REDACTED***Price Note:  My price here is to cover what I paid for the rifle, AK mag-release lock, shipping and tax, everything you'd pay except transfer fees when buying one of these rifles and having it shipped to your local FFL, saving you the steps of having to do that of course.  I'm actually taking a little hit on the price since I paid the outrageous transfer fees you do when you have a rifle shipped in from an online seller (totalled $111 for me this time), and you'll only have to pay the $25 or $30 private party transfer fee you find at most FFL's, which there are a few locally here that I know of who do it.  So, if you're driving from Sac or something (to Chico) the differrence would cover your fuel costs.  Plus, you're getting your hands on a DDI AK, which if you know what you're looking at, nuff said.  Since it's brand new, and super hard to get a hold of since they fly off the shelves, this thing is definitely worth the full price, and then some.  A quick search will find you NO other DDI AK's in the entire state of CA for sale, just to give you an idea of how many people are willing to sell these things once they've gotten their hands on one.***

postcontent: CALL TO VERIFY IN STOCK STATUS BEFORE DRIVING TO STORE OR BUYING ONLINE>Steyr Arms SSG Carbon .308 Winchester 23.6" Barrel MFG # 66.55355.050480aSteyr Arms SSG Carbon .308 Winchester 23.6" Barrel MFG # 66.55355.050480aThe Steyr SSG Carbon is the newest addition to the SSG family, and this rifle takes high-performance long-range shooting into the future with a compound carbon-fiber stock that creates a benchmark of extreme strength and durability. Unlike conventional carbon-fiber stocks made from woven carbon fabric that often suffer from side-strike structural failures, the SSG Carbon's stock is made using the same "chipped-carbon" Sheet Molding Compound (SMC) construction used to create load-bearing structures in Formula 1 racecars and high-performance aircraft. The SSG Carbon's chipped-carbon flakes combine thermally with the binding agent to form the SMC fror a distinctive appearance to the stock, but like the spirals on the rifle's cold hammer-forged barrel, they aren't just there for looks. The carbon chips interlock with each other to create an unparalleled tension net that is superior to steel in every direction, yet weighing a fraction of either steel or aluminum.Due to the unique recoil absorption properties of its SMC technology, the SSG Carbon is surprisingly lightweight, and its recoil absorption is unmatched. Utilizing the same barreled action and muzzle brake as the famed SSG 08, the SSG Carbon utilizes a direct trigger, legendary for its crisp, clean and repeatable break. A detachable box magazine functions either as a constant-feed magazine or it can be placed in a second position that acts as a magazine cutoff to single-feed the rifle over the tip of a loaded magazine.The SSG Carbon is built on the Safe Bolt System (SBS) action with a unique 2+1 safety function that offers three settings operated by a wheel switch on the tang of the stock. The FIRE mode (safety off) is indicated by a red dot, and the first level of SAFE mode disables the firing mechanism while allowing the bolt to be cycled. The second SAFE position locks the bolt, at which point the bolt can be pushed down against the stock, locking the firing pin and firing mechanism out of firing position, allowing safe transportation with a round in the chamber. Simply pressing the safety's release tab and rolling it forward returns the bolt to either the SAFE or the FIRE position.The stock of the SSG Carbon has multiple mounting points for sling attachments. It also features an adjustable cheek piece, an adjustable butt plate, rubber-wrapped pistol grip, and an integrated finely adjustable rear-elevation pod. Available in a choice of the widely used caliber sizes of .308 Winchester or 300 Winchester Magnum, this platform provides high-precision performance and proven reliability.The .308 Winchester magazine holds 10 rounds and is available in either a 23.6-inch Heavy Barrel version or a 20-inch heavy barrel compact version. Both options feature a muzzle brake as well as a durable synthetic stock with an adjustable length-of-pull-- via stackable buttplate inserts-- and an adjustable cheek piece.As in other Steyr high-performance bolt-action rifles, the SSG 04 is built on the Safe Bolt System (SBS) action with a unique 2+1 safety function that offers three settings operated by a wheel switch on the tang of the stock. The FIRE mode (safety off) is indicated by a red dot, and the first level of SAFE mode disables the firing mechanism while allowing the bolt to be cycled. The second SAFE position locks the bolt, at which point the bolt can be pushed down against the stock, locking the firing pin and firing mechanism out of firing position, allowing safe transportation with a round in the chamber. Simply pressing the safety's release tab and rolling it forward returns the bolt to either the SAFE or the FIRE position. The receiver is topped with a Picatinny rail for optics mounting.Another feature in the SSG 04 is the 2-stage magazine securing mechanism that uses a first stage to lock the magazine in but allows the bolt to be operated without feeding rounds in the magazine, thereby providing the user with the options of dry-firing or loading individual rounds by hand while maintaining a full magazine at the ready. Simply pressing up on the bottom of the magazine seats it in the second stage, which is ready for auto-loading.The SSG 04 A1 is also available by special order. The SSG 04 A1 replaces the standard Picatinny rail with a shroud that is attached to the receiver and covers the barrel for the length of the forend.
